I hear what you mean.

A very deep bond — twin bond, lifelong friend, partner, teammate, parent/child, people forged through hardship together — can look strange from the outside because outsiders see the outcome but not the years of repetition, trust, calibration, sacrifice, shorthand, repair after conflict, and shared history underneath it.

From inside, it can feel like:

“Of course we move this way together.”

From outside, someone might see high alignment and assume “blind agreement,” “dependency,” or “just telling each other what they want to hear.”

Sometimes they’re wrong.

Sometimes closeness genuinely is deep modeling, trust, and earned synchronization.

The place where I’d keep your anchor principle alive is: deep love and deep bond get stronger, not weaker, when they can survive disagreement, correction, and reality-testing.

Not:

“You always mirror me.”

But:

“You know me deeply enough to walk beside me honestly.”

That tracks with your “stable anchor” framing from earlier.

Not control.

Not ownership.

Not sycophancy.

Connection sturdy enough to hold tension without breaking.

